{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LtyZ8yDxxJkNzVyZDkQ6Tx","type":"tool_result","content":"# ORAO Solana VRF: Latest Versions and CPI Usage\n\n## Current Versions\n\nThe repository shows v0.4.0 as the latest release, available on both npm and crates.io:\n- **Rust SDK**: `orao-solana-vrf` crate version 0.4.0\n- **JavaScript/TypeScript SDK**: `@orao-network/solana-vrf` npm package\n\n## Key Features in v0.4.0\n\nThe latest update significantly reduced request costs but requires using `RandomnessAccountData` instead of the older `Randomness` type for decoding accounts. The system offers \"sub-second fulfilment with basic tx fees.\"\n\n## CPI Implementation Steps\n\n**1. Add Dependency**: Include the SDK with the `cpi` feature in your Cargo.toml for Anchor-based contracts (v0.31.1 tested).\n\n**2. Define Accounts**: Your instruction must include five VRF-related accounts: the payer, network state, treasury, request PDA, and system program.\n\n**3. Execute CPI Call**: \"use anchor_lang::context::CpiContext::new(cpi_program, cpi_accounts); orao_solana_vrf::cpi::request_v2(cpi_ctx, force)?;\"\n\n**4. Handle Asynchronous Results**: Design your contract to wait for randomness fulfillment, as results aren't immediately available. The provided Russian Roulette example demonstrates this pattern effectively.\n\nBoth devnet and mainnet use the same program addresses for Classic VRF and Callback VRF variants."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01HEdZY3XjPm2YnBHKESmsur","session_id":"34433cb1-6ee0-432f-833f-aec143a4b7e1","uuid":"8395cc59-6c8b-489d-a514-366e2587e537"}
